      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i have a biology test coming up and im super confused about photosynthesis. can u explain the difference between the light-dependent reactions and the calvin cycle? like what actually happens in each part?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The light-dependent reactions occur in the thylakoid membranes and use light energy to split water molecules, release oxygen, and generate energy carriers (ATP and NADPH). In contrast, the Calvin cycle takes place within the stroma of the chloroplast and uses that stored ATP and NADPH to convert carbon dioxide into glucose. While the first phase captures energy from sunlight, the second phase utilizes that energy to build sugar molecules necessary for plant growth. Understanding this flow—from light capture to carbon fixation—is key to how plants produce food.",
